                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-235-person1961">
                  ABRAHAM 
                  JAMES
               <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1961" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1961" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1961" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in <placeName id="t18320705-235-crimeloc1238">Russell-mews</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320705-235-crimeloc1238" type="placeName" value="Russell-mews"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320705-235-crimeloc1238" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-235-off1236 t18320705-235-crimeloc1238"></join> with my son William, who is a <rs id="t18320705-235-viclabel1239" type="occupation">livery-stable keeper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-235-victim1960 t18320705-235-viclabel1239"></join> - the prisoner was in his employ about eight months ago. On the 29th of June, about half-past six o'clock in the morning, when I went into the stable, he was there, and asked how I did; I said, "I don't know you;" he said, "Yes you do, I worked here for your son some time ago;" I said, "I have no knowledge of you;" he said, "He told me he had a set of harness for sale;" I said, "I know he has not, for his harness is in use;" he said, "This is the harness with the lion on it;" I said that was not for sale, for it was a glass-coach harness; he unbuckled the pad; I went up stairs to speak to my son, who was asleep, and when I came down he was gone, with the bridle and pad; I found him about a week after, and asked him about it - he said it was not sold, but he knew where it was; I asked him to give me the address where it was - he said he would not; he did not say it was in pledge; I afterwards found it at a pawnbroker's, in Seven-dials.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did you not take the bridle and pad, and put them on my arm? A. I did not; I never said I would not prosecute you if I received 8s.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-235-person1962">
                  JAMES 
                  ALDOUS
               <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1962" type="surname" value="ALDOUS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1962" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1962" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. On the 29th of June a pad and a bridle were pawned by the prisoner; I have known him twenty years.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-235-person1963">
                  JOSEPH 
                  WILKINS
               <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1963" type="surname" value="WILKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1963" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1963" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I received him in charge last Thursday night - he said he would return<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183206050104"></xptr>the harness in the morning, or 2l. 10s.; he produced the duplicate of it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence (written). I called upon the prosecutor's son - he asked me to sell the harness; the prosecutor himself gave me the articles laid in the indictment, to show to hackneymen, to see if I could dispose of them, but being extremely old, although I had tried to sell them, I could not succeed; being very much distressed and fatigued, I called at Mr. Aldous, in Berwick-street, Soho, and pledged them for 1s. 6d., fully intending to redeem them, and return them to the owner - after I had received them from the prosecutor he wished me good-day, saying, that he had no money to treat me, and I said neither had I any.</p>
               <p>- WILLIE. The prisoner sent for me the evening he was taken, and I saw Mr. James, who said to me,"God bless my soul! I don't think the man has taken it with intent to steal it;" I said, "I believe he has not;" he said, "Will you call on me?" I called that evening at his place - he then said he did not think he took it with intent to steal it and not bring it back, but he did not bring it back for a week, and he was afraid his son would make him pay for it; I said I would make a bridle and pad to match rather than he should be taken - he said, "Well, I think I would take 8s. and drop it, if my expenses are paid;" I said as I had known Charters so long I did not mind that.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-235-person1964">
                  ABRAHAM 
                  JAMES
               <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1964" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1964" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-235-person1964" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I never saw the witness but once till he was before the Magistrate; I did not tell him I believed the prisoner did not intend to steal it, nor offer to make it up for 8s. and my expences - he followed me about from time to time, and wanted me to go and drink with him; since I have been here he has also followed me about.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320705-235-verdict1240" type="verdictDescription">
